Below is a **single‑file, self‑contained** C‑to‑C++ binding for the BlockSci block iterator.  
It contains

* a clean, pure‑C public header that a C program can include, and  
* a C++ implementation (guard‑ed by `#ifdef __cplusplus`) that translates the C API to the native BlockSci C++ objects.

The design follows the “callback‑per‑row” pattern used by libraries such as pandas/Polars: the user supplies a function that is invoked for every block, the function can abort the walk early, and the data that the callback sees is a *view* into the internal BlockSci structures – no copies are made, keeping the hot path as cheap as possible.

```c
/*=====================================================================
   blockscic.h   –  C bindings for the BlockSci block iterator
   =====================================================================

   * Public C API (usable from pure C)
   * C++ implementation (compiled only when a C++ compiler includes this
     header).  The file can be compiled as a shared library and linked
     against the BlockSci static/dynamic library.

   Build example (Linux):

       g++ -std=c++17 -fPIC -shared -o libblockscic.so \
           -I/path/to/blocksci/include \
           -L/path/to/blocksci/lib -lblocksci \
           blockscic.h

   Then a C program can link with `-lblockscic`.

   ------------------------------------------------------------------ */
#ifndef BLOCKSCI_C_H
#define BLOCKSCI_C_H

/*--------------------------------------------------------------------
   C PUBLIC INTERFACE
   --------------------------------------------------------------------*/
#ifdef __cplusplus
extern "C" {
#endif

#include <stddef.h>
#include <stdint.h>

/* Opaque handles – the actual layout is defined in the C++ part */
typedef struct block_iterator_t block_iterator_t;
typedef struct block_t          block_t;

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Callback type.
   The iterator passes a pointer to a `block_t` that is valid only for
   the duration of the call.  Return 0 to keep iterating, any non‑zero
   value aborts the walk and that value is returned from the iterator
   function.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
typedef int (*block_callback_t)(const block_t *block, void *user_data);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Creation / destruction
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
block_iterator_t *block_iterator_new(const char *db_path);
/* Returns NULL on error – see `block_iterator_last_error()` for details */
void block_iterator_free(block_iterator_t *it);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Error handling
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
/* Thread‑local error string (NULL if no error).  The pointer stays valid
   until the next call that sets an error. */
const char *block_iterator_last_error(void);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Core iteration routine.
   Returns:
     0   – success (walk completed)
     >0 – value returned by the user callback (early abort)
    -1   – null iterator or callback
    -2   – exception thrown inside the walk
    -3   – unknown internal failure
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
int block_iterator_for_each(block_iterator_t *it,
                            block_callback_t   cb,
                            void              *user_data);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Accessors – all pointers are valid only while the callback is active.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
uint64_t block_height(const block_t *blk);
uint64_t block_timestamp(const block_t *blk);
uint32_t block_tx_count(const block_t *blk);

/* Returns a pointer to the raw 32‑byte block hash and its length.
   The pointer is valid only for the duration of the callback. */
const uint8_t *block_hash(const block_t *blk, size_t *out_len);

#ifdef __cplusplus
} /* extern "C" */
#endif

/*=====================================================================
   C++ IMPLEMENTATION (included automatically when compiled as C++)
   =====================================================================*/
#ifdef __cplusplus

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Include the real BlockSci headers.  Adjust the include path to match
   your installation.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
#include <blocksci/chain/chain.hpp>   // provides blocksci::Chain, blocksci::Block
#include <exception>
#include <memory>
#include <string>
#include <vector>

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Opaque structures – the layout is deliberately hidden from C code.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
struct block_iterator_t {
    /* The Chain object owns the whole blockchain data set. */
    std::unique_ptr<blocksci::Chain> chain;

    /* Iterators over the vector of blocks that BlockSci provides. */
    std::vector<blocksci::Block>::iterator cur;
    std::vector<blocksci::Block>::iterator end;
};

struct block_t {
    /* A non‑owning pointer into the vector owned by `block_iterator_t`. */
    const blocksci::Block *impl;
};

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Thread‑local storage for the last error string.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
static thread_local std::string last_error;

/* Helper to set the thread‑local error message */
static void set_error(const std::string &msg) { last_error = msg; }

extern "C" {

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Error query
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
const char *block_iterator_last_error(void) {
    return last_error.empty() ? nullptr : last_error.c_str();
}

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Create a new iterator.
   Throws are caught and translated to a NULL return value.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
block_iterator_t *block_iterator_new(const char *db_path) {
    try {
        if (!db_path) {
            set_error("db_path is null");
            return nullptr;
        }

        auto *it = new block_iterator_t;
        it->chain = std::make_unique<blocksci::Chain>(db_path);
        it->cur   = it->chain->blocks().begin();
        it->end   = it->chain->blocks().end();
        return it;
    } catch (const std::exception &e) {
        set_error(e.what());
        return nullptr;
    } catch (...) {
        set_error("unknown error while constructing iterator");
        return nullptr;
    }
}

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Destroy an iterator.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
void block_iterator_free(block_iterator_t *it) {
    delete it;   // unique_ptr cleans up the Chain object automatically
}

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Accessors – thin wrappers around the native BlockSci API.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
uint64_t block_height(const block_t *blk) {
    return static_cast<uint64_t>(blk->impl->height());
}
uint64_t block_timestamp(const block_t *blk) {
    return static_cast<uint64_t>(blk->impl->timestamp());
}
uint32_t block_tx_count(const block_t *blk) {
    return static_cast<uint32_t>(blk->impl->tx_count());
}
const uint8_t *block_hash(const block_t *blk, size_t *out_len) {
    /* BlockSci stores the hash as a std::array<uint8_t,32>. */
    const auto &h = blk->impl->hash();
    if (out_len) *out_len = h.size();
    return h.data();
}

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Core iteration routine.
   The hot loop is deliberately simple:
     * No heap allocation per block.
     * A single reusable `block_t` struct is passed to the callback.
     * The callback receives a *const* pointer – it cannot modify the
       underlying BlockSci object, preserving thread‑safety.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
int block_iterator_for_each(block_iterator_t *it,
                            block_callback_t   cb,
                            void              *user_data) {
    if (!it) {
        set_error("iterator pointer is null");
        return -1;
    }
    if (!cb) {
        set_error("callback pointer is null");
        return -1;
    }

    try {
        block_t view;                     // reused for every iteration
        for (; it->cur != it->end; ++it->cur) {
            view.impl = &*it->cur;        // point at the current block
            int rc = cb(&view, user_data);
            if (rc != 0) {                // non‑zero means early abort
                return rc;               // propagate the user‑provided code
            }
        }
        return 0;                        // walked the whole collection
    } catch (const std::exception &e) {
        set_error(e.what());
        return -2;
    } catch (...) {
        set_error("unknown exception during iteration");
        return -3;
    }
}

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   End of extern "C"
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
} /* extern "C" */

#endif /* __cplusplus */

#endif /* BLOCKSCI_C_H */
```

### How a C program uses the API

```c
#include "blockscic.h"
#include <stdio.h>

int my_block_cb(const block_t *blk, void *user_data) {
    uint64_t height = block_height(blk);
    uint64_t ts     = block_timestamp(blk);
    uint32_t  ntx   = block_tx_count(blk);
    size_t    hlen;
    const uint8_t *hash = block_hash(blk, &hlen);

    /* Example: print the first 5 000 000 blocks and then stop */
    if (height < 5000000) {
        printf("block %llu: ts=%llu tx=%u hash=", (unsigned long long)height,
               (unsigned long long)ts, ntx);
        for (size_t i = 0; i < hlen; ++i) printf("%02x", hash[i]);
        putchar('\n');
    } else {
        return 1;               /* abort the walk */
    }
    return 0;                   /* continue */
}

int main(void) {
    block_iterator_t *it = block_iterator_new("/path/to/blocksci/db");
    if (!it) {
        fprintf(stderr, "failed to open DB: %s\n",
                block_iterator_last_error());
        return 1;
    }

    int rc = block_iterator_for_each(it, my_block_cb, NULL);
    if (rc < 0) {
        fprintf(stderr, "iteration error: %s\n",
                block_iterator_last_error());
    } else if (rc > 0) {
        printf("iteration stopped early by callback (code %d)\n", rc);
    } else {
        printf("walk completed successfully\n");
    }

    block_iterator_free(it);
    return 0;
}
```

### Why this is fast

| Feature | Reason it matters for a hot 800 M‑iteration loop |
|---------|---------------------------------------------------|
| **No per‑block allocation** | The `block_t` view is allocated once on the stack and reused. |
| **Zero‑copy view** | The callback sees a `const` pointer into the BlockSci vector; no data is duplicated. |
| **Early‑abort support** | The iterator stops as soon as the user callback returns a non‑zero value, avoiding needless work. |
| **Thread‑local error storage** | No global lock contention when reporting errors. |
| **Pure‑C ABI** | The callback is a plain C function pointer; the compiler can inline the call in the hot loop (the compiler sees the call‑target as an external function, but the overhead is just the indirect call). |
| **Minimal indirection** | All the work is done inside the `for` loop; the only extra operation is the indirect call to `cb`. |

The binding can be compiled with maximum optimisation (`-O3 -march=native`) and linked against the highly‑optimised BlockSci library, giving a per‑block overhead that is essentially just the indirect call to the user’s function. This mirrors the design of pandas/Polars where the user‑supplied row function is called for each row with a view of the underlying data.
